<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>NOSEBLEED / EPISTAXIS</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="Case_sheet_styles.css" id="light-styles">
    <link id="dark-styles" rel="alternate stylesheet" title="dark" href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css">
    <script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
  </head>
  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode"> Dark Mode</button>
    <div class="ent General">
      <h3>1<sup>ST</sup> COMPLAINT: <strong>NOSEBLEED (EPISTAXIS)</strong></h3>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>:
            Site, Laterality &amp; Direction of Flow</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent"><b>Which side?</b> Right / Left / Both (did it start
              on one side?)</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Where does it feel like it&rsquo;s coming from?</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="ent"><b>Anterior (front of nose)</b>: blood from
                  nostril, often visible source (common; usually
                  Kiesselbach&rsquo;s area).</li>
                <li class="ent emergency"><b>Posterior (back of nose)</b>: blood
                  mainly going down the throat, coughing/spitting blood, hard to
                  see a source (more likely severe/arterial).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="General"><b>Confirm its nose</b> (important mimics):
              <ul>
                <li class="respiratory"><b>Coughing blood (haemoptysis)</b>
                  rather than nasal bleeding?</li>
                <li class="git"><b>Vomiting blood (haematemesis)</b> or
                  &ldquo;coffee-ground&rdquo; vomit?</li>
                <li class="ent"><b>Bleeding from gums/throat</b> or mouth
                  ulcers?</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Which nostril is the bleeding coming from? Does it
          come out the front, or does it feel like it&rsquo;s dripping down the
          back of your throat? Just to be sure, were you coughing it up or
          vomiting it, or did it clearly start in the nose?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>O</strong>:
            Onset &amp; Trigger</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent"><b>Spontaneous</b> (no obvious trigger)</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Local trauma / irritation</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="ent">Nose picking / scratching, vigorous nose
                  blowing, sneezing fits</li>
                <li class="ent surgery">Facial/nasal injury, recent nasal
                  surgery, nasal cautery</li>
                <li class="ent">Foreign body (esp. children), nasal piercings</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="ent infectious"><b>URTI / sinus symptoms</b> (blocked
              nose, discharge, facial pressure, fever)</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Allergic rhinitis</b> (itching, sneezing, watery
              rhinorrhoea)</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Environment</b> (winter heating, dry air, high
              altitude, hot environment)</li>
            <li class="psychiatric ent"><b>drugs</b>: cocaine (septal
              irritation/perforation risk)</li>
            <li class="General"><b>Exertional </b>: heavy lifting/straining,
              intense exercise</li>
            <li class="obstetric"><b>Pregnancy</b> (nasal congestion, increased
              vascularity)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How did it start? Did anything trigger it &mdash;
          blowing your nose, sneezing, picking, an injury, an infection,
          allergies, dry air, or straining? Any recent nasal surgery or use of
          recreational drugs like cocaine?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>D</strong>:
            Duration, Frequency &amp; Control</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="General"><b>Duration of each episode</b>: seconds /
              minutes / &gt;10&ndash;15 minutes / &gt;20 minutes</li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Prolonged bleeding</b> despite correct
              first aid is significant (especially &gt;20 minutes).</li>
            <li class="General"><b>Frequency</b>: first episode vs recurrent;
              how many in last week/month?</li>
            <li class="General"><b>Stopping measures</b> (and whether they
              worked):
              <ul>
                <li class="ent">Lean forward (not back)</li>
                <li class="ent">Pinch soft part of the nose firmly and
                  continuously</li>
                <li class="ent">Cold compress/ice pack</li>
                <li class="ent">Any nasal spray used to stop it (e.g.,
                  decongestant)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Need for medical help?</b> GP/ED
              attendance, nasal packing, cautery, hospital admission, blood
              transfusion.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How long did the bleeding last each time, and how
          often has it happened? Were you able to stop it yourself &mdash;
          leaning forward and pinching the soft part of your nose continuously
          &mdash; or did you need medical help like packing or cautery?"</span>
      </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>A/R</strong>:
            Aggravating &amp; Relieving Factors</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="General"><b>Aggravating</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="ent">Nose blowing, sneezing, hot showers, dry air</li>
                <li class="General">Alcohol binge, strenuous exercise,
                  straining/constipation</li>
                <li class="cvs">Poorly controlled blood pressure</li>
                <li class="ent">Topical nasal irritation (decongestant overuse,
                  intranasal steroids if misdirected)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="General"><b>Relieving</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="ent">Correct first aid: forward lean + continuous
                  pressure</li>
                <li class="ent">Humidification / saline sprays / petroleum-free
                  moisturisers for dryness</li>
                <li class="General">Avoiding triggers (alcohol/straining) for a
                  few days after an episode</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Does anything reliably trigger it or make it
          worse? And what helps &mdash; pressure, leaning forward, ice, or
          anything else?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>C</strong>:
            Character &amp; Estimated Volume</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent"><b>Type</b>: slow ooze / intermittent drip /
              continuous flow / &ldquo;gushing&rdquo;</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Clots</b>: none vs large/multiple clots</li>
            <li class="General"><b>Estimate volume</b> (use practical anchors):
              <ul>
                <li class="General">Number of soaked tissues/cloths</li>
                <li class="General">Blood in sink / cupfuls</li>
                <li class="General">Blood on pillow (night-time bleeds)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="cvs cns"><b>Symptoms of significant blood loss</b>:
              dizziness, fainting, palpitations, breathlessness on exertion,
              chest pain.</li>
            <li class="hematology"><b>Symptoms of anaemia</b>: fatigue, reduced
              exercise tolerance, pica, pale appearance.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Can you describe it &mdash; was it a trickle or a
          heavy flow? Were there clots? Roughly how much blood do you think you
          lost, and did you feel dizzy, faint, breathless, or your heart
          racing?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>:
            Recurrence &amp; Previous Episodes</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="General"><b>Previous history</b>: childhood nosebleeds vs
              new-onset in adulthood</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Side consistency</b>: always same nostril
              (consider local lesion if recurrent and unilateral)</li>
            <li class="ent"><b>Seasonal pattern</b>: winter/dry months, allergy
              seasons</li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Previous interventions</b>: cautery,
              packing, surgery; any complications.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Is this the first time, or have you had nosebleeds
          before? If it&rsquo;s recurrent, is it always the same side and have
          you ever needed cautery or packing?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>A</strong>:
            Associated Symptoms &amp; Risk Factors</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent"><b>Local nasal symptoms</b> (think inflammation,
              septal disease, tumour)
              <ul>
                <li class="ent">Nasal blockage (especially <b>unilateral</b>)</li>
                <li class="ent">Facial pain/pressure, dental pain, numbness,
                  epiphora</li>
                <li class="ent">Reduced smell, crusting, foul smell</li>
                <li class="ent">Visible nasal mass / persistent scabbing</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="hematology"><b>Bleeding tendency (personal &amp; family)</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="hematology">Easy bruising, petechiae</li>
                <li class="hematology">Bleeding gums, prolonged bleeding from
                  cuts</li>
                <li class="hematology">Previous excessive bleeding after dental
                  work/surgery/childbirth</li>
                <li class="hematology">Family history of bleeding disorders
                  (e.g., von Willebrand disease)</li>
                <li class="ent hematology">Recurrent nosebleeds + telangiectasia
                  (lips/tongue/fingertips) or family history (consider HHT)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="gynob hematology"><b>Menstrual history (if relevant)</b>:
              heavy periods, flooding, clots, iron deficiency symptoms</li>
            <li class="General"><b>Medication &amp; substances</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="hematology"><b>Anticoagulants</b> (warfarin/DOACs), <b>antiplatelets</b>
                  (aspirin/clopidogrel)</li>
                <li class="General"><b>NSAIDs</b>, SSRIs/SNRIs (can increase
                  bleeding risk), herbal supplements (e.g., ginkgo)</li>
                <li class="ent">Intranasal steroids / decongestants (technique
                  and overuse)</li>
                <li class="psychiatric ent">Cocaine or intranasal drug use</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="General"><b>Medical conditions</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="cvs">Hypertension (and control/medication adherence)</li>
                <li class="git">Liver disease / alcohol excess (coagulopathy)</li>
                <li class="Nephro">Chronic kidney disease/uraemia (platelet
                  dysfunction)</li>
                <li class="hematology">Known thrombocytopenia,
                  leukaemia/lymphoma, anticoagulation issues</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li class="General"><b>Safeguarding / context (if applicable)</b>
              <ul>
                <li class="General">Unexplained injury pattern</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Any blocked nose (especially one-sided), facial
          pain, crusting, or a lump in the neck? Do you bruise easily or bleed
          elsewhere? Have you had heavy bleeding after dental work or
          operations, or is there a family history? What medicines do you take
          &mdash; especially blood thinners, aspirin, or anti-inflammatories
          &mdash; and any cocaine use?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>:
            Progression</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="General">Getting more frequent</li>
            <li class="General">Getting heavier / harder to stop</li>
            <li class="ent">New associated nasal symptoms (obstruction, facial
              pain, crusting)</li>
            <li class="hematology">New bruising/bleeding elsewhere</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Are the nosebleeds becoming more frequent,
          heavier, or harder to stop? Have any new symptoms appeared alongside
          them?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>P</strong>:
            Pattern</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent">Time-of-day: mornings / at night</li>
            <li class="ent">Seasonal: winter dryness / allergy seasons</li>
            <li class="General">Trigger-linked: alcohol / exercise / straining</li>
            <li class="ent">Always same nostril</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Is there any pattern &mdash; particular times of
          day, seasons, triggers, or always the same side?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>E</strong>:
            Effect on Life</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="General">Anxiety/fear of recurrence</li>
            <li class="General">Sleep disturbance (night-time bleeds)</li>
            <li class="General">Missed work/school, social limitation</li>
            <li class="General">Impact of ED visits/admissions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"How has this been affecting you day-to-day &mdash;
          sleep, work, and anxiety about it happening again?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>R</strong>:
            Red Flags &amp; Safety-net</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Prolonged or severe bleeding</b>
              (typically &gt;20 minutes) or not responding to firm continuous
              pressure.</li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Suspected posterior epistaxis</b>:
              heavy bleeding with blood mainly down the throat, bilateral
              bleeding, or recurrent bleeding despite first aid.</li>
            <li class="cvs cns emergency"><b>Shock / haemodynamic compromise</b>:
              fainting, marked dizziness, extreme pallor, chest pain, collapse.</li>
            <li class="respiratory emergency"><b>Breathing difficulty</b> or
              aspiration risk (copious blood in throat).</li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Large/multiple clots</b> or vomiting
              swallowed blood.</li>
            <li class="hematology emergency"><b>On anticoagulants</b> with
              heavy/prolonged bleeding, or suspected bleeding disorder.</li>
            <li class="ent emergency"><b>Recurrent unilateral epistaxis</b> with
              new one-sided obstruction, facial pain/numbness, persistent
              crusting, or neck lump.</li>
            <li class="ent hematology emergency"><b>Adolescent male</b> with
              recurrent unilateral epistaxis + nasal blockage (consider juvenile
              nasopharyngeal angiofibroma).</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"I&rsquo;m going to quickly check for warning
          signs: bleeding that won&rsquo;t stop after firm pressure, blood going
          mainly down the throat, feeling faint or unwell, breathing difficulty,
          large clots or vomiting blood, being on blood thinners, or a one-sided
          blocked nose or neck lump." </span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>S</strong>:
            Severity / Bother Scale</span> </div>
        <span class="verbal">"On a scale of 1 to 10, how severe or worrying have
          these nosebleeds been for you?"</span> </div>
      <div class="point">
        <div class="point-content"> <span class="description"><strong>D/D</strong>:
            Common Causes to Consider</span>
          <ul>
            <li class="ent">Local irritation/trauma (digital trauma, dryness,
              septal spurs/perforation)</li>
            <li class="ent infectious">Rhinitis/rhinosinusitis</li>
            <li class="ent">Allergic rhinitis</li>
            <li class="hematology">Anticoagulation/antiplatelets or systemic
              bleeding tendency</li>
            <li class="cvs">Hypertension (association with severity/recurrence,
              especially in older adults)</li>
            <li class="ent hematology">Structural lesions/tumours (persistent
              unilateral symptoms, mass, neck nodes)</li>
            <li class="ent hematology">Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia
              (recurrent epistaxis + telangiectasia/family history)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <span class="verbal">"Based on your answers, we consider common causes
          like dryness or irritation, infection or allergy, medicines that thin
          the blood, and&mdash;rarely&mdash;structural problems in the nose if
          it&rsquo;s recurrent and one-sided."</span> </div>
    </div>
